{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652085"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18508"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18508"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.05,0.8,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76306"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11237"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61814"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7461"},{"type":"tags","id":"7463"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26313"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76306"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lateral ligament complex of the ankle is an important anatomical structure that provides stability to the lateral ankle joint.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the components of the lateral ligament complex of the ankle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deltoid and spring ligaments","Spring and anterior talofibular ligaments","Anterior talofibular, calcaneofibular, and posterior talofibular ligaments","Interosseous and anterior tibiofibular ligaments","Anterior and posterior tibiofibular ligaments"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lateral ligament complex of the ankle consists of three distinct ligaments: the \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior talofibular (ATFL), calcaneofibular (CFL), and posterior talofibular ligaments (PTFL) (image)\u003C/strong\u003E. These ligaments work together to provide lateral stability to the ankle joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeltoid and spring ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E - These ligaments are located on the medial aspect of the ankle and provide medial stability\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpring and anterior talofibular ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E - While the anterior talofibular ligament is part of the lateral complex, the spring ligament is a medial structure supporting the longitudinal arch of the foot\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterosseous and anterior tibiofibular ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E - These are components of the tibiofibular syndesmosis, not the lateral ligament complex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior and posterior tibiofibular ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E - These syndesmotic ligaments connect the tibia to the fibula above the ankle joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior talofibular ligament is the most commonly injured ankle ligament, followed by the calcaneofibular ligament. The posterior talofibular ligament is the strongest and least commonly injured of the three.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The lateral ligament complex of the ankle consists of three distinct ligaments: anterior talofibular, calcaneofibular, and posterior talofibular.","The anterior talofibular ligament connects the lateral malleolus to the talus and resists anterior translation and inversion.","The calcaneofibular ligament runs from the lateral malleolus to the calcaneus and provides stability during inversion."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cLateral collateral ligament of ankle joint\u201d by Laboratoires Servier\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Lateral_collateral_ligament_of_ankle_joint.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61814"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18508"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21412"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21412"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/A0UJ0ltHthIwOLMZvFppgKiiALWoVo.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/A0UJ0ltHthIwOLMZvFppgKiiALWoVo.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":458}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61814"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T03:02:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T03:05:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11237"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76306"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{